data.content:
Here's what happened and how to fix it:

## The Problem

In C# 14, new built-in `Span<T>` conversions change overload resolution. When you write `array.Contains(num)`, the compiler now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (a `Span`-based method) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`**. Expression trees **cannot represent Span-based method calls**, so this throws at runtime.

## The Fix

Force the call to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting to `IEnumerable<T>` or using `.AsEnumerable()`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast the array
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static invocation
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these ensures the expression tree uses `Enumerable.Contains`, which is representable in an expression tree. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` and any other LINQ methods on arrays that now resolve to `Span` extensions.
